3.breadcrumbs: Generation V » Universal » Code Injection » Code Injection Guide (Generation V)
3.title: Code Injection Guide (Generation V)

4.body: Extract a ROM in the Games tab of CTRMap with the Add ROM button. Close CTRMap. In File Explorer, go to the folder where the jar for CTRMap is located. In the address bar, type cmd to open the command line in that folder. After this, run java -cp "<ctrmap file name>" ctrmap.util.tools.ovl.CodeInjectionSystemGUI replacing <ctrmap file name> with the name of your CTRMap jar. This will launch OvlPatchSystemGUI, also known as C Injection System GUI (CISGUI). Click File > Open game directory then open the folder that CTRMap created when extracting the contents of your ROM. After this, locate esdb.yml and open that. This file holds information about function names along with the "segment" (ARM9/Overlay) that the function from and their addresses the function will load at in RAM. You will be prompted to install the built-in overlay loader. Select No since this loader is deprecated. Click the + button at the bottom left and load arm9_decmp_off_HK_REL.rpm. This should be located in the build/ folder in the PMC folder. This will allow you to keep your arm9 decompressed along with letting the game load normally. After this, click the + button again to load PMC.rpm. At this point, you can now use dlls placed in the vfs/data/patches/ folder of your project.
4.breadcrumbs: Generation V » Universal » Code Injection » Preparing a project for C injected code
4.title: Preparing a project for C injected code

5.body: This section assumes you have basic C knowledge and have also used Bond697's IDB before. Install the arm-none-eabi version of GCC . Make sure you use the installer. Write whatever C code you'd like to inject. Usually for this, you'll want to figure out an existing function that would be easy to work off of. If you want to see IDA's attempt at decompiling the Assembly, press F5. This isn't always necessarily accurate when it comes to types, but it's often a good starting point. In File Explorer, go to the folder where armgcc.bat is located. In the address bar, type cmd to open the command line in that folder. After this, enter armgcc <c source file location> -Iswan/ <desired output file location>.elf, replacing <c source file location> and desired output file location>. The -Iswan/ makes the compiler include whatever folder a header file is in as long as it's in the swan/ folder. This can be replaced with -I<folder name> if needed. Click Tools > Convert ELF to RPM then save the RPM. After that, click Tools > Convert RPM to DLL. Save this DLL in vfs/data/patches/ in the folder of a project to make use of it.
